# 🐧 Experiment: File & Directory Management in Linux

## 🎯 Aim
To carry out file and directory management tasks in Linux, and to understand file permissions along with basic text editors.

## 📌 Objectives
- Navigate within the Linux file system 🧭
- Create and manage files and directories 📁
- Understand and modify file permissions 🔐
- Use text editors such as nano and vi ✏️

## 📖 Theory

### 📂 Linux File System
The Linux file system follows a hierarchical structure that starts from the root directory /. All files and directories are arranged in a tree-like format, which ensures efficient organization and strong security.

### 📁 Files and Directories
- Files are used to store data such as text, scripts, or programs. 📄
- Directories are used to organize files and other directories. 🗂️

### 🔐 File and Directory Permissions
Linux uses a permission-based model to control access to files and directories:
- Read (r) allows viewing the contents 👁️
- Write (w) allows modifying the contents ✍️
- Execute (x) allows running a file as a program ▶️

Permissions are assigned to three categories: Owner, Group, and Others.

### ✏️ Text Editors
- nano is a simple and beginner-friendly editor. 🟢
- vi is an advanced and powerful editor commonly available on Linux systems. 🔧

## ⚙️ Procedure

1. Logged into the Linux virtual machine. 💻
2. Opened the terminal application. 🖥️
3. Displayed the current working directory using the command pwd. 📍
4. Listed files and directories in the current location using ls and ls -l. 📋
5. Created a new directory named linux_lab using mkdir linux_lab and moved into it using cd linux_lab. 📂
6. Created two empty files inside the directory using touch file1.txt file2.txt. 📄
7. Edited file1.txt using the nano editor by typing nano file1.txt. Typed some text, saved the file using Ctrl + O, and exited nano using Ctrl + X. ✏️💾
8. Edited file2.txt using the vi editor by typing vi file2.txt. Pressed i to enter insert mode, typed some text, then pressed Esc followed by :wq to save and quit. ✏️💾
9. Displayed the contents of file1.txt using the command cat file1.txt. 👀
10. Checked file permissions for all files using ls -l. 🔍
11. Modified file permissions for file1.txt using chmod 755 file1.txt. 🔧
12. Verified the updated permissions using ls -l file1.txt. ✅

## 🛠️ Configuration Commands Used
The following commands were practiced during this experiment: pwd, ls, ls -l, cd, mkdir, touch, cat, nano, vi, chmod.

## 📊 Observations / Results
- Files and directories were created successfully. ✅
- Text files were edited using both nano and vi editors without errors. ✅
- File contents were displayed correctly using the cat command. ✅
- File permissions were viewed and successfully modified using chmod. ✅

## 🎯 Conclusion
The experiment was completed successfully. ✅ File and directory management operations were performed effectively. The concept of file permissions was understood and applied. Hands-on experience was gained with text editors and basic file handling in Linux. 🐧
